A study on vitamin D and cancer risk revealed that fair-skinned individuals need 10-15 minutes of sun exposure, while darker-skinned individuals may need up to 25 minutes.
Taking 2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily can reduce cancer risk by 50%.
Research showed lower breast cancer rates with higher vitamin D levels.
Experts suggest 1,000 IU daily for cancer prevention.
Sun exposure helps produce vitamin D, reducing cancer risk.
The study highlights the importance of maintaining adequate vitamin D levels to prevent various cancers, emphasizing the role of sunlight and supplements in cancer prevention.
